function GetParablesData(){return Parables.data}var Parables={data:[{lessontitle:"The Good Samaritan",lessonscriptures:"Luke\\10:25-37",id:"1",verses:"{I}{B}WEB\\Luke\\10:25-37{/I}{/B}{BR}{BR}25  Behold, a certain lawyer stood up and tested him, saying, Teacher, what shall I do to inherit eternal life?\r {BR}26  He said to him, {I}{B}What is written in the law? How do you read it?{/B}{/I}\r {BR}27  He answered, You shall love the Lord your God with all your heart, with all your soul, with all your strength, and with all your mind; and your neighbor as yourself.\r {BR}28  He said to him, {I}{B}You have answered correctly. Do this, and you will live.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}29  But he, desiring to justify himself, asked Jesus, Who is my neighbor?\r {BR}30  Jesus answered, {I}{B}A certain man was going down from Jerusalem to Jericho, and he fell among robbers, who both stripped him and beat him, and departed, leaving him half dead.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}31  {I}{B}By chance a certain priest was going down that way. When he saw him, he passed by on the other side.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}32  {I}{B}In the same way a Levite also, when he came to the place, and saw him, passed by on the other side.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}33  {I}{B}But a certain Samaritan, as he traveled, came where he was. When he saw him, he was moved with compassion,{/B}{/I}\r {BR}34  {I}{B}came to him, and bound up his wounds, pouring on oil and wine. He set him on his own animal, and brought him to an inn, and took care of him.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}35  {I}{B}On the next day, when he departed, he took out two denarii, and gave them to the host, and said to him, 'Take care of him. Whatever you spend beyond that, I will repay you when I return.'{/B}{/I}\r {BR}36  {I}{B}Now which of these three do you think seemed to be a neighbor to him who fell among the robbers?{/B}{/I}\r {BR}37  He said, He who showed mercy on him. Then Jesus said to him, {I}{B}Go and do likewise.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}{BR}"},{lessontitle:"The Lost Sheep, Coin, Son",lessonscriptures:"Luke\\15:1-32",id:"2",verses:"{I}{B}WEB\\Luke\\15:1-32{/I}{/B}{BR}{BR}1  Now all the tax collectors and sinners were coming close to him to hear him.\r {BR}2  The Pharisees and the scribes murmured, saying, This man welcomes sinners, and eats with them.\r {BR}3  He told them this parable.\r {BR}4  {I}{B}Which of you men, if you had one hundred sheep, and lost one of them, wouldn't leave the ninety-nine in the wilderness, and go after the one that was lost, until he found it?{/B}{/I}\r {BR}5  {I}{B}When he has found it, he carries it on his shoulders, rejoicing.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}6  {I}{B}When he comes home, he calls together his friends and his neighbors, saying to them, 'Rejoice with me, for I have found my sheep which was lost!'{/B}{/I}\r {BR}7  {I}{B}I tell you that even so there will be more joy in heaven over one sinner who repents, than over ninety-nine righteous people who need no repentance.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}8  {I}{B}Or what woman, if she had ten drachma coins, if she lost one drachma coin, wouldn't light a lamp, sweep the house, and seek diligently until she found it?{/B}{/I}\r {BR}9  {I}{B}When she has found it, she calls together her friends and neighbors, saying, 'Rejoice with me, for I have found the drachma which I had lost.'{/B}{/I}\r {BR}10  {I}{B}Even so, I tell you, there is joy in the presence of the angels of God over one sinner repenting.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}11  He said, {I}{B}A certain man had two sons.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}12  {I}{B}The younger of them said to his father, 'Father, give me my share of your property.' He divided his livelihood between them.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}13  {I}{B}Not many days after, the younger son gathered all of this together and traveled into a far country. There he wasted his property with riotous living.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}14  {I}{B}When he had spent all of it, there arose a severe famine in that country, and he began to be in need.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}15  {I}{B}He went and joined himself to one of the citizens of that country, and he sent him into his fields to feed pigs.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}16  {I}{B}He wanted to fill his belly with the husks that the pigs ate, but no one gave him any.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}17  {I}{B}But when he came to himself he said, 'How many hired servants of my father's have bread enough to spare, and I'm dying with hunger!{/B}{/I}\r {BR}18  {I}{B}I will get up and go to my father, and will tell him, Father, I have sinned against heaven, and in your sight.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}19  {I}{B}I am no more worthy to be called your son. Make me as one of your hired servants. '{/B}{/I}\r {BR}20  {I}{B}He arose, and came to his father. But while he was still far off, his father saw him, and was moved with compassion, and ran, and fell on his neck, and kissed him.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}21  {I}{B}The son said to him, 'Father, I have sinned against heaven, and in your sight. I am no longer worthy to be called your son.'{/B}{/I}\r {BR}22  {I}{B}But the father said to his servants, 'Bring out the best robe, and put it on him. Put a ring on his hand, and shoes on his feet.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}23  {I}{B}Bring the fattened calf, kill it, and let us eat, and celebrate;{/B}{/I}\r {BR}24  {I}{B}for this, my son, was dead, and is alive again. He was lost, and is found.' They began to celebrate.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}25  {I}{B}Now his elder son was in the field. As he came near to the house, he heard music and dancing.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}26  {I}{B}He called one of the servants to him, and asked what was going on.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}27  {I}{B}He said to him, 'Your brother has come, and your father has killed the fattened calf, because he has received him back safe and healthy.'{/B}{/I}\r {BR}28  {I}{B}But he was angry, and would not go in. Therefore his father came out, and begged him.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}29  {I}{B}But he answered his father, 'Behold, these many years I have served you, and I never disobeyed a commandment of yours, but you never gave me a goat, that I might celebrate with my friends.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}30  {I}{B}But when this, your son, came, who has devoured your living with prostitutes, you killed the fattened calf for him.'{/B}{/I}\r {BR}31  {I}{B}He said to him, 'Son, you are always with me, and all that is mine is yours.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}32  {I}{B}But it was appropriate to celebrate and be glad, for this, your brother, was dead, and is alive again. He was lost, and is found.' {/B}{/I}\r {BR}{BR}"},{lessontitle:"The Pharisee And Tax Collector",lessonscriptures:"Luke\\18:9-14",id:"3",verses:"{I}{B}WEB\\Luke\\18:9-14{/I}{/B}{BR}{BR}9  He spoke also this parable to certain people who were convinced of their own righteousness, and who despised all others.\r {BR}10  {I}{B}Two men went up into the temple to pray; one was a Pharisee, and the other was a tax collector.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}11  {I}{B}The Pharisee stood and prayed to himself like this: 'God, I thank you, that I am not like the rest of men, extortioners, unrighteous, adulterers, or even like this tax collector.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}12  {I}{B}I fast twice a week. I give tithes of all that I get.'{/B}{/I}\r {BR}13  {I}{B}But the tax collector, standing far away, wouldn't even lift up his eyes to heaven, but beat his breast, saying, 'God, be merciful to me, a sinner!'{/B}{/I}\r {BR}14  {I}{B}I tell you, this man went down to his house justified rather than the other; for everyone who exalts himself will be humbled, but he who humbles himself will be exalted.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}{BR}"},{lessontitle:"The Rich Fool",lessonscriptures:"Luke\\12:13-21",id:"4",verses:"{I}{B}WEB\\Luke\\12:13-21{/I}{/B}{BR}{BR}13  One of the multitude said to him, Teacher, tell my brother to divide the inheritance with me.\r {BR}14  But he said to him, {I}{B}Man, who made me a judge or an arbitrator over you?{/B}{/I}\r {BR}15  He said to them, {I}{B}Beware! Keep yourselves from covetousness, for a man's life doesn't consist of the abundance of the things which he possesses.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}16  He spoke a parable to them, saying, {I}{B}The ground of a certain rich man brought forth abundantly.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}17  {I}{B}He reasoned within himself, saying, 'What will I do, because I don't have room to store my crops?'{/B}{/I}\r {BR}18  {I}{B}He said, 'This is what I will do. I will pull down my barns, and build bigger ones, and there I will store all my grain and my goods.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}19  {I}{B}I will tell my soul, Soul, you have many goods laid up for many years. Take your ease, eat, drink, be merry. '{/B}{/I}\r {BR}20  {I}{B}But God said to him, 'You foolish one, tonight your soul is required of you. The things which you have prepared-whose will they be?'{/B}{/I}\r {BR}21  {I}{B}So is he who lays up treasure for himself, and is not rich toward God.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}{BR}"},{lessontitle:"The Rich Man And Lazarus",lessonscriptures:"Luke\\16:19-31",id:"5",verses:"{I}{B}WEB\\Luke\\16:19-31{/I}{/B}{BR}{BR}19  {I}{B}Now there was a certain rich man, and he was clothed in purple and fine linen, living in luxury every day.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}20  {I}{B}A certain beggar, named Lazarus, was laid at his gate, full of sores,{/B}{/I}\r {BR}21  {I}{B}and desiring to be fed with the crumbs that fell from the rich man's table. Yes, even the dogs came and licked his sores.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}22  {I}{B}It happened that the beggar died, and that he was carried away by the angels to Abraham's bosom. The rich man also died, and was buried.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}23  {I}{B}In Hades, he lifted up his eyes, being in torment, and saw Abraham far off, and Lazarus at his bosom.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}24  {I}{B}He cried and said, 'Father Abraham, have mercy on me, and send Lazarus, that he may dip the tip of his finger in water, and cool my tongue! For I am in anguish in this flame.'{/B}{/I}\r {BR}25  {I}{B}But Abraham said, 'Son, remember that you, in your lifetime, received your good things, and Lazarus, in like manner, bad things. But now here he is comforted and you are in anguish.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}26  {I}{B}Besides all this, between us and you there is a great gulf fixed, that those who want to pass from here to you are not able, and that none may cross over from there to us.'{/B}{/I}\r {BR}27  {I}{B}He said, 'I ask you therefore, father, that you would send him to my father's house;{/B}{/I}\r {BR}28  {I}{B}for I have five brothers, that he may testify to them, so they won't also come into this place of torment.'{/B}{/I}\r {BR}29  {I}{B}But Abraham said to him, 'They have Moses and the prophets. Let them listen to them.'{/B}{/I}\r {BR}30  {I}{B}He said, 'No, father Abraham, but if one goes to them from the dead, they will repent.'{/B}{/I}\r {BR}31  {I}{B}He said to him, 'If they don't listen to Moses and the prophets, neither will they be persuaded if one rises from the dead.' {/B}{/I}\r {BR}{BR}"},{lessontitle:"The Sheep And The Goats",lessonscriptures:"Matthew\\25:31-46",id:"6",verses:"{I}{B}WEB\\Matthew\\25:31-46{/I}{/B}{BR}{BR}31  {I}{B}But when the Son of Man comes in his glory, and all the holy angels with him, then he will sit on the throne of his glory.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}32  {I}{B}Before him all the nations will be gathered, and he will separate them one from another, as a shepherd separates the sheep from the goats.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}33  {I}{B}He will set the sheep on his right hand, but the goats on the left.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}34  {I}{B}Then the King will tell those on his right hand, 'Come, blessed of my Father, inherit the Kingdom prepared for you from the foundation of the world;{/B}{/I}\r {BR}35  {I}{B}for I was hungry, and you gave me food to eat. I was thirsty, and you gave me drink. I was a stranger, and you took me in.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}36  {I}{B}I was naked, and you clothed me. I was sick, and you visited me. I was in prison, and you came to me.'{/B}{/I}\r {BR}37  {I}{B}Then the righteous will answer him, saying, 'Lord, when did we see you hungry, and feed you; or thirsty, and give you a drink?{/B}{/I}\r {BR}38  {I}{B}When did we see you as a stranger, and take you in; or naked, and clothe you?{/B}{/I}\r {BR}39  {I}{B}When did we see you sick, or in prison, and come to you?'{/B}{/I}\r {BR}40  {I}{B}The King will answer them, 'Most certainly I tell you, inasmuch as you did it to one of the least of these my brothers, you did it to me.'{/B}{/I}\r {BR}41  {I}{B}Then he will say also to those on the left hand, 'Depart from me, you cursed, into the eternal fire which is prepared for the devil and his angels;{/B}{/I}\r {BR}42  {I}{B}for I was hungry, and you didn't give me food to eat; I was thirsty, and you gave me no drink;{/B}{/I}\r {BR}43  {I}{B}I was a stranger, and you didn't take me in; naked, and you didn't clothe me; sick, and in prison, and you didn't visit me.'{/B}{/I}\r {BR}44  {I}{B}Then they will also answer, saying, 'Lord, when did we see you hungry, or thirsty, or a stranger, or naked, or sick, or in prison, and didn't help you?'{/B}{/I}\r {BR}45  {I}{B}Then he will answer them, saying, 'Most certainly I tell you, inasmuch as you didn't do it to one of the least of these, you didn't do it to me.'{/B}{/I}\r {BR}46  {I}{B}These will go away into eternal punishment, but the righteous into eternal life.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}{BR}"},{lessontitle:"The Sower",lessonscriptures:"Matthew\\13:1-9;Matthew\\13:18-23",id:"7",verses:"{I}{B}WEB\\Matthew\\13:1-9{/I}{/B}{BR}{BR}1  On that day Jesus went out of the house, and sat by the seaside.\r {BR}2  Great multitudes gathered to him, so that he entered into a boat, and sat, and all the multitude stood on the beach.\r {BR}3  He spoke to them many things in parables, saying, {I}{B}Behold, a farmer went out to sow.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}4  {I}{B}As he sowed, some seeds fell by the roadside, and the birds came and devoured them.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}5  {I}{B}Others fell on rocky ground, where they didn't have much soil, and immediately they sprang up, because they had no depth of earth.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}6  {I}{B}When the sun had risen, they were scorched. Because they had no root, they withered away.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}7  {I}{B}Others fell among thorns. The thorns grew up and choked them.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}8  {I}{B}Others fell on good soil, and yielded fruit: some one hundred times as much, some sixty, and some thirty.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}9  {I}{B}He who has ears to hear, let him hear.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}{BR}{I}{B}WEB\\Matthew\\13:18-23{/I}{/B}{BR}{BR}18  {I}{B}Hear, then, the parable of the farmer.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}19  {I}{B}When anyone hears the word of the Kingdom, and doesn't understand it, the evil one comes, and snatches away that which has been sown in his heart. This is what was sown by the roadside.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}20  {I}{B}What was sown on the rocky places, this is he who hears the word, and immediately with joy receives it;{/B}{/I}\r {BR}21  {I}{B}yet he has no root in himself, but endures for a while. When oppression or persecution arises because of the word, immediately he stumbles.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}22  {I}{B}What was sown among the thorns, this is he who hears the word, but the cares of this age and the deceitfulness of riches choke the word, and he becomes unfruitful.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}23  {I}{B}What was sown on the good ground, this is he who hears the word, and understands it, who most certainly bears fruit, and brings forth, some one hundred times as much, some sixty, and some thirty.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}{BR}"},{lessontitle:"The Ten Bridesmaids",lessonscriptures:"Matthew\\25:1-13",id:"8",verses:"{I}{B}WEB\\Matthew\\25:1-13{/I}{/B}{BR}{BR}1  {I}{B}Then the Kingdom of Heaven will be like ten virgins, who took their lamps, and went out to meet the bridegroom.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}2  {I}{B}Five of them were foolish, and five were wise.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}3  {I}{B}Those who were foolish, when they took their lamps, took no oil with them,{/B}{/I}\r {BR}4  {I}{B}but the wise took oil in their vessels with their lamps.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}5  {I}{B}Now while the bridegroom delayed, they all slumbered and slept.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}6  {I}{B}But at midnight there was a cry, 'Behold! The bridegroom is coming! Come out to meet him!'{/B}{/I}\r {BR}7  {I}{B}Then all those virgins arose, and trimmed their lamps.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}8  {I}{B}The foolish said to the wise, 'Give us some of your oil, for our lamps are going out.'{/B}{/I}\r {BR}9  {I}{B}But the wise answered, saying, 'What if there isn't enough for us and you? You go rather to those who sell, and buy for yourselves.'{/B}{/I}\r {BR}10  {I}{B}While they went away to buy, the bridegroom came, and those who were ready went in with him to the marriage feast, and the door was shut.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}11  {I}{B}Afterward the other virgins also came, saying, 'Lord, Lord, open to us.'{/B}{/I}\r {BR}12  {I}{B}But he answered, 'Most certainly I tell you, I don't know you.'{/B}{/I}\r {BR}13  {I}{B}Watch therefore, for you don't know the day nor the hour in which the Son of Man is coming.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}{BR}"},{lessontitle:"The Three Servants (talents)",lessonscriptures:"Matthew\\25:14-30",id:"9",verses:"{I}{B}WEB\\Matthew\\25:14-30{/I}{/B}{BR}{BR}14  {I}{B}For it is like a man, going into another country, who called his own servants, and entrusted his goods to them.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}15  {I}{B}To one he gave five talents, to another two, to another one; to each according to his own ability. Then he went on his journey.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}16  {I}{B}Immediately he who received the five talents went and traded with them, and made another five talents.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}17  {I}{B}In like manner he also who got the two gained another two.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}18  {I}{B}But he who received the one went away and dug in the earth, and hid his lord's money.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}19  {I}{B}Now after a long time the lord of those servants came, and reconciled accounts with them.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}20  {I}{B}He who received the five talents came and brought another five talents, saying, 'Lord, you delivered to me five talents. Behold, I have gained another five talents besides them.'{/B}{/I}\r {BR}21  {I}{B}His lord said to him, 'Well done, good and faithful servant. You have been faithful over a few things, I will set you over many things. Enter into the joy of your lord.'{/B}{/I}\r {BR}22  {I}{B}He also who got the two talents came and said, 'Lord, you delivered to me two talents. Behold, I have gained another two talents besides them.'{/B}{/I}\r {BR}23  {I}{B}His lord said to him, 'Well done, good and faithful servant. You have been faithful over a few things, I will set you over many things. Enter into the joy of your lord.'{/B}{/I}\r {BR}24  {I}{B}He also who had received the one talent came and said, 'Lord, I knew you that you are a hard man, reaping where you did not sow, and gathering where you did not scatter.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}25  {I}{B}I was afraid, and went away and hid your talent in the earth. Behold, you have what is yours.'{/B}{/I}\r {BR}26  {I}{B}But his lord answered him, 'You wicked and slothful servant. You knew that I reap where I didn't sow, and gather where I didn't scatter.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}27  {I}{B}You ought therefore to have deposited my money with the bankers, and at my coming I should have received back my own with interest.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}28  {I}{B}Take away therefore the talent from him, and give it to him who has the ten talents.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}29  {I}{B}For to everyone who has will be given, and he will have abundance, but from him who doesn't have, even that which he has will be taken away.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}30  {I}{B}Throw out the unprofitable servant into the outer darkness, where there will be weeping and gnashing of teeth.'{/B}{/I}\r {BR}{BR}"},{lessontitle:"The Two Foundations",lessonscriptures:"Matthew\\7:24-27",id:"10",verses:"{I}{B}WEB\\Matthew\\7:24-27{/I}{/B}{BR}{BR}24  {I}{B}Everyone therefore who hears these words of mine, and does them, I will liken him to a wise man, who built his house on a rock.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}25  {I}{B}The rain came down, the floods came, and the winds blew, and beat on that house; and it didn't fall, for it was founded on the rock.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}26  {I}{B}Everyone who hears these words of mine, and doesn't do them will be like a foolish man, who built his house on the sand.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}27  {I}{B}The rain came down, the floods came, and the winds blew, and beat on that house; and it fell-and great was its fall.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}{BR}"},{lessontitle:"The Unforgiving Servant",lessonscriptures:"Matthew\\18:21-35",id:"11",verses:"{I}{B}WEB\\Matthew\\18:21-35{/I}{/B}{BR}{BR}21  Then Peter came and said to him, Lord, how often shall my brother sin against me, and I forgive him? Until seven times?\r {BR}22  Jesus said to him, {I}{B}I don't tell you until seven times, but, until seventy times seven.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}23  {I}{B}Therefore the Kingdom of Heaven is like a certain king, who wanted to reconcile accounts with his servants.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}24  {I}{B}When he had begun to reconcile, one was brought to him who owed him ten thousand talents.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}25  {I}{B}But because he couldn't pay, his lord commanded him to be sold, with his wife, his children, and all that he had, and payment to be made.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}26  {I}{B}The servant therefore fell down and kneeled before him, saying, 'Lord, have patience with me, and I will repay you all!'{/B}{/I}\r {BR}27  {I}{B}The lord of that servant, being moved with compassion, released him, and forgave him the debt.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}28  {I}{B}But that servant went out, and found one of his fellow servants, who owed him one hundred denarii, and he grabbed him, and took him by the throat, saying, 'Pay me what you owe!'{/B}{/I}\r {BR}29  {I}{B}So his fellow servant fell down at his feet and begged him, saying, 'Have patience with me, and I will repay you!'{/B}{/I}\r {BR}30  {I}{B}He would not, but went and cast him into prison, until he should pay back that which was due.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}31  {I}{B}So when his fellow servants saw what was done, they were exceedingly sorry, and came and told to their lord all that was done.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}32  {I}{B}Then his lord called him in, and said to him, 'You wicked servant! I forgave you all that debt, because you begged me.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}33  {I}{B}Shouldn't you also have had mercy on your fellow servant, even as I had mercy on you?'{/B}{/I}\r {BR}34  {I}{B}His lord was angry, and delivered him to the tormentors, until he should pay all that was due to him.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}35  {I}{B}So my heavenly Father will also do to you, if you don't each forgive your brother from your hearts for his misdeeds.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}{BR}"},{lessontitle:"The Wedding Feast",lessonscriptures:"Matthew\\22:1-14",id:"12",verses:"{I}{B}WEB\\Matthew\\22:1-14{/I}{/B}{BR}{BR}1  Jesus answered and spoke again in parables to them, saying,\r {BR}2  {I}{B}The Kingdom of Heaven is like a certain king, who made a marriage feast for his son,{/B}{/I}\r {BR}3  {I}{B}and sent out his servants to call those who were invited to the marriage feast, but they would not come.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}4  {I}{B}Again he sent out other servants, saying, 'Tell those who are invited, Behold, I have made ready my dinner. My cattle and my fatlings are killed, and all things are ready. Come to the marriage feast! '{/B}{/I}\r {BR}5  {I}{B}But they made light of it, and went their ways, one to his own farm, another to his merchandise,{/B}{/I}\r {BR}6  {I}{B}and the rest grabbed his servants, and treated them shamefully, and killed them.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}7  {I}{B}When the king heard that, he was angry, and sent his armies, destroyed those murderers, and burned their city.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}8  {I}{B}Then he said to his servants, 'The wedding is ready, but those who were invited weren't worthy.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}9  {I}{B}Go therefore to the intersections of the highways, and as many as you may find, invite to the marriage feast.'{/B}{/I}\r {BR}10  {I}{B}Those servants went out into the highways, and gathered together as many as they found, both bad and good. The wedding was filled with guests.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}11  {I}{B}But when the king came in to see the guests, he saw there a man who didn't have on wedding clothing,{/B}{/I}\r {BR}12  {I}{B}and he said to him, 'Friend, how did you come in here not wearing wedding clothing?' He was speechless.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}13  {I}{B}Then the king said to the servants, 'Bind him hand and foot, take him away, and throw him into the outer darkness; there is where the weeping and grinding of teeth will be.'{/B}{/I}\r {BR}14  {I}{B}For many are called, but few chosen.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}{BR}"},{lessontitle:"The Widow And The Judge",lessonscriptures:"Luke\\18:1-8",id:"13",verses:"{I}{B}WEB\\Luke\\18:1-8{/I}{/B}{BR}{BR}1  He also spoke a parable to them that they must always pray, and not give up,\r {BR}2  saying, {I}{B}There was a judge in a certain city who didn't fear God, and didn't respect man.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}3  {I}{B}A widow was in that city, and she often came to him, saying, 'Defend me from my adversary!'{/B}{/I}\r {BR}4  {I}{B}He wouldn't for a while, but afterward he said to himself, 'Though I neither fear God, nor respect man,{/B}{/I}\r {BR}5  {I}{B}yet because this widow bothers me, I will defend her, or else she will wear me out by her continual coming.' {/B}{/I}\r {BR}6  The Lord said, {I}{B}Listen to what the unrighteous judge says.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}7  {I}{B}Won't God avenge his chosen ones, who are crying out to him day and night, and yet he exercises patience with them?{/B}{/I}\r {BR}8  {I}{B}I tell you that he will avenge them quickly. Nevertheless, when the Son of Man comes, will he find faith on the earth?{/B}{/I}\r {BR}{BR}"},{lessontitle:"Workers In The Vineyard",lessonscriptures:"Matthew\\20:1-16",id:"14",verses:"{I}{B}WEB\\Matthew\\20:1-16{/I}{/B}{BR}{BR}1  {I}{B}For the Kingdom of Heaven is like a man who was the master of a household, who went out early in the morning to hire laborers for his vineyard.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}2  {I}{B}When he had agreed with the laborers for a denarius a day, he sent them into his vineyard.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}3  {I}{B}He went out about the third hour, and saw others standing idle in the marketplace.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}4  {I}{B}To them he said, 'You also go into the vineyard, and whatever is right I will give you.' So they went their way.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}5  {I}{B}Again he went out about the sixth and the ninth hour, and did likewise.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}6  {I}{B}About the eleventh hour he went out, and found others standing idle. He said to them, 'Why do you stand here all day idle?'{/B}{/I}\r {BR}7  {I}{B}They said to him, 'Because no one has hired us.' He said to them, 'You also go into the vineyard, and you will receive whatever is right.'{/B}{/I}\r {BR}8  {I}{B}When evening had come, the lord of the vineyard said to his manager, 'Call the laborers and pay them their wages, beginning from the last to the first.'{/B}{/I}\r {BR}9  {I}{B}When those who were hired at about the eleventh hour came, they each received a denarius.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}10  {I}{B}When the first came, they supposed that they would receive more; and they likewise each received a denarius.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}11  {I}{B}When they received it, they murmured against the master of the household,{/B}{/I}\r {BR}12  {I}{B}saying, 'These last have spent one hour, and you have made them equal to us, who have borne the burden of the day and the scorching heat!'{/B}{/I}\r {BR}13  {I}{B}But he answered one of them, 'Friend, I am doing you no wrong. Didn't you agree with me for a denarius?{/B}{/I}\r {BR}14  {I}{B}Take that which is yours, and go your way. It is my desire to give to this last just as much as to you.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}15  {I}{B}Isn't it lawful for me to do what I want to with what I own? Or is your eye evil, because I am good?'{/B}{/I}\r {BR}16  {I}{B}So the last will be first, and the first last. For many are called, but few are chosen.{/B}{/I}\r {BR}{BR}"}],tablename:"Parables"};